<TITLE> Elections once reforms are over: Fakhruddin </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 9 (bdnews24.com)  Interim government head Fakhruddin Ahmed has told the European Union's Troika delegation that his administration will arrange elections after the ongoing reforms and hand over power soon. He also said the people's support is their biggest power. A 10-member Troika delegation that met the chief adviser at his office Saturday discussed reforms, election timeframe, parlour politics, proposed budget and formation of a national human rights commission. They also discussed the government move to allow people to participate in the budget for the first time and strengthen the local government. The EU delegates praised the interim government for the steps and promised financial assistance and help in holding elections, the chief adviser's press secretary Syed Fahim Munaim told the media. The chief adviser told them the government will allow parlour politics at a proper time. He said the Election Commission would announce a clear roadmap to the national election in the middle of July. Fakhruddin said the press was working freely and it was working as a link between the government and the people in the absence of parliament. The chief adviser also told the delegation that the government was being able to know people's views through the media and likewise, the people are getting to know the government's activities through the media. He said people's views have been sought about the national budget, which has created opportunity for the common people to participate in the budget discussion. Committees have been formed to strengthen the local government institutions. He also told the delegation that work was under way to form a national human rights commission. Andreas Michaelis, the delegation leader, said Bangladesh has an active media and civil society. bdnews24.c
